I am writing to highlight a critical issue with the Screener-2 evaluation queue.

“I don’t know why the entire AI community on LinkedIn is not talking about this today.

Yesterday, the folks at Thinking Machines published their first blog post:

 👉 “Defeating Nondeterminism in LLM Inference.”

It tackles one of the most overlooked issues in AI systems: reproducibility.

We all know LLMs feel “random”, ask the same question twice, get two different answers. But what’s shocking is that even at temperature 0, when outputs should be deterministic, still behave nondeterministically.

Why?
 Most people blame GPU concurrency + floating point quirks. But Horace’s post shows the real culprit:
 🔹 Lack of batch invariance in inference kernels.
 🔹 Meaning: your answer can change depending on how many other users are hitting the server at the same time.

The blog goes deep into:
- Why operations like RMSNorm, Matmul, and Attention break determinism.
- How to re-engineer kernels to achieve true batch-invariance.
- Proof that with these fixes, you can get bitwise-identical outputs across runs.
- And why this unlocks things like true on-policy RL for training, something previously impossible.

This is a game-changer. Reliable AI research, reproducible enterprise apps, and trustworthy scientific results all depend on fixing nondeterminism.

My 2 cents: This is one of those “boring infrastructure” breakthroughs that quietly redefines what’s possible. Everyone building with LLMs should pay attention.”

Currently, the team often acts based on internal decisions without fully considering miners’ perspectives. I understand Plasma is very busy and constantly dealing with thousands of requests, and I also recognize that until now Plasma has acted fairly and reasonably toward miners. This subnet is highly time-sensitive, and with many platform bugs, timely DM responses are often necessary. If the platform were fully automated and bug-free, such issues would not arise. Ignoring or blocking many miners under these circumstances risks harming the subnet’s reputation.

Therefore, Plasma, I respectfully ask that clear written rules be established first. Once they are posted, applying penalties for violations will be both fair and transparent.
